import java.util.*;

class TweetCounts {
    private Map<String, List<Integer>> tweets;

    public TweetCounts() {
        tweets = new HashMap<>();
    }

    public void recordTweet(String tweetName, int time) {
        tweets.computeIfAbsent(tweetName, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(time);
    }

    public List<Integer> getTweetCountsPerFrequency(String freq, String tweetName, int startTime, int endTime) {
        List<Integer> times = tweets.getOrDefault(tweetName, Collections.emptyList());
        int chunk;
        switch (freq) {
            case "minute": chunk = 60; break;
            case "hour":   chunk = 3600; break;
            case "day":    chunk = 86400; break;
            default: throw new IllegalArgumentException();
        }
        int n = (endTime - startTime) / chunk + 1;
        int[] counts = new int[n];
        for (int t : times) {
            if (t < startTime || t > endTime) continue;
            int idx = (t - startTime) / chunk;
            counts[idx]++;
        }
        List<Integer> res = new ArrayList<>(n);
        for (int c : counts) res.add(c);
        return res;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(1) for recordTweet, O(K) for getTweetCountsPerFrequency where K is the number of tweets for the given tweetName
space complexity: O(N) where N is the total number of recorded tweets
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Store each tweet's timestamp in a list per tweetName. For queries, compute chunk size from freq, then count tweets in each chunk by direct index calculation. Simple array counting avoids sorting and binary search overhead.

